1
00:00:30,090 --> 00:00:33,600
If you're clear about
your feelings, don't deny them.

2
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:36,120
He just put that money together.
And it vanished just like that.

3
00:00:36,540 --> 00:00:39,750
These scammers are truly rotten.
When will they get rid of them?

4
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:48,020
Mom.

5
00:01:00,840 --> 00:01:03,480
I've made a huge mistake.

6
00:01:31,300 --> 00:01:32,300
Mom...

7
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:37,880
I can't face anyone anymore.

8
00:02:04,120 --> 00:02:05,640
It's okay.

9
00:02:56,810 --> 00:02:57,810
Dad.

10
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:00,600
Eat something.

11
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:03,040
Thanks.

12
00:03:04,100 --> 00:03:05,760
Anything from the police?

13
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:09,160
Not yet, Dad.

14
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:15,760
Dad, anything you want to eat,
just say the word.

15
00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:20,880
Hey, Dad.

16
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:23,680
If something's bothering you,
tell us.

17
00:03:23,800 --> 00:03:26,120
If it gets too heavy,
I'll take you to a doctor.

18
00:03:28,120 --> 00:03:31,040
Always a doctor for everything?

19
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:35,040
I'm not that fragile.

20
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:38,800
I still have plenty of fight left
to look after all of you.

21
00:03:39,860 --> 00:03:43,520
You're all holding it together
for my sake

22
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:46,520
I can't just lie here
and fall apart.

23
00:03:47,630 --> 00:03:51,030
As for the money they took...
I've made my peace with it.

24
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:53,870
It's better to spend time
earning it back.

25
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:22,840
Sure he's really doing better?

26
00:04:23,353 --> 00:04:25,233
Seems like it.
That's what he said, anyway.

27
00:04:26,599 --> 00:04:29,239
Hope he wouldn't just say things
to put us at ease.

28
00:04:29,280 --> 00:04:31,920
No, no. He's not that kind of man.

29
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:36,680
He bounces back just like that.
That's just who he is.

30
00:04:37,310 --> 00:04:38,440
He wouldn't put on a front.

31
00:04:48,020 --> 00:04:49,020
Hmm.

32
00:05:50,030 --> 00:05:51,560
Mom, keep a close eye on Grandpa.

33
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:54,000
Don't leave him alone.

34
00:05:55,960 --> 00:05:58,520
If anything comes up, call me
and I'll head straight back.

35
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:02,600
Achoo.

36
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:08,920
Achoo.

37
00:06:11,070 --> 00:06:12,070
Achoo.

38
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:20,320
You okay?

39
00:06:24,390 --> 00:06:25,480
Come on. Clear your nose.

40
00:06:26,490 --> 00:06:27,720
Cut it out. I'll handle it.

41
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:29,880
I don't mind at all.

42
00:06:33,620 --> 00:06:35,030
Hey, wait.

43
00:06:37,146 --> 00:06:38,146
What now?

44
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:45,880
Whoa, you're burning up.

45
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:48,440
Just a little fever.

46
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Come with me.

47
00:06:58,250 --> 00:06:59,250
Let go.

48
00:07:00,910 --> 00:07:02,080
Don't be stubborn.

49
00:07:02,360 --> 00:07:03,790
You're not worried someone'll see?

50
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:06,200
Why would I be?

51
00:07:06,460 --> 00:07:09,460
You said we should
keep our distance at school.

52
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:13,960
You want us to walk,
or you want me to carry you?

53
00:07:14,650 --> 00:07:15,840
You can't carry me.

54
00:07:16,120 --> 00:07:17,120
Wanna bet?

55
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:20,240
Hey, no. I can walk.

56
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:24,320
When I hurt my foot, you walked me
to the nurse's office.

57
00:07:25,080 --> 00:07:26,360
It's my turn.

58
00:07:30,120 --> 00:07:31,120
Go.

59
00:07:42,410 --> 00:07:44,240
I'm not dying; it's just a cold.

60
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:49,280
You look pretty rough.

61
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:51,680
Where'd you catch it?

62
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:53,800
From my boyfriend.

63
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,000
Boyfriend?

64
00:07:56,250 --> 00:07:57,460
When did you have a boyfriend?

65
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:00,480
Whenever I want.
None of your business.

66
00:08:01,400 --> 00:08:03,960
Guy, quit being funny.

67
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:06,120
Seriously.

68
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:09,240
Good you brought him. Let him rest.

69
00:08:11,410 --> 00:08:12,410
H'choo.

70
00:08:14,640 --> 00:08:15,800
Atchoo!

71
00:08:16,840 --> 00:08:17,840
Tchoo!

72
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:24,840
Kru (teacher), I picked up...
a cold from him.

73
00:08:25,410 --> 00:08:27,800
I can tell when someone's faking it.

74
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:30,560
Break's over. Out you go.

75
00:08:33,230 --> 00:08:34,230
Yes, Kru.

76
00:08:38,720 --> 00:08:41,520
Guy, get serious.
A boyfriend, really?

77
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:46,360
Hmm.

78
00:08:48,100 --> 00:08:49,280
Heh...Kru (teacher).

79
00:09:05,340 --> 00:09:09,600
"Sorry, the number you dialed
is unavailable at this time."

80
00:09:11,510 --> 00:09:12,510
Huh.

81
00:09:13,890 --> 00:09:14,930
He has a boyfriend?

82
00:09:29,610 --> 00:09:30,610
Oh.

83
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:35,040
Grandpa.

84
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:37,680
Can you write again now?

85
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:39,440
Mm-hmm, here.

86
00:09:40,350 --> 00:09:41,510
I've gotten a lot done.

87
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:43,950
Should be ready to post tomorrow.

88
00:09:44,680 --> 00:09:47,610
Don't push yourself too hard.
You'll be aching all over again.

89
00:09:47,810 --> 00:09:48,810
Hmph.

90
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:52,640
See? Stiff, isn't it?

91
00:09:54,080 --> 00:09:55,120
Press right here for me.

92
00:09:56,330 --> 00:09:57,330
Right here?

93
00:09:57,740 --> 00:09:59,000
Ow, ow...hmm.

94
00:09:59,720 --> 00:10:02,000
Mmm...so tight.

95
00:10:03,350 --> 00:10:06,400
Save, I owe you an apology.

96
00:10:07,240 --> 00:10:09,200
For losing all our money like that.

97
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:14,080
Don't apologize. This isn't on you.

98
00:10:14,800 --> 00:10:15,920
It's on the scammers.

99
00:10:17,360 --> 00:10:20,960
Everyone knows how much

100
00:10:21,920 --> 00:10:23,840
you've given for this family.

101
00:10:24,830 --> 00:10:25,950
Nobody blames you.

102
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:34,660
That's enough.

103
00:10:41,890 --> 00:10:42,890
Hmm?

104
00:10:48,220 --> 00:10:49,840
Why do you have a magnifying glass?

105
00:10:50,320 --> 00:10:53,520
No reason. Found it while
going through some things.

106
00:10:58,470 --> 00:10:59,470
Hmm.

107
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:06,400
Ajarn Thaworn,
the Writers' Association is calling.

108
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:08,280
Oh, give me that.

109
00:11:15,510 --> 00:11:16,510
Hello.

110
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:18,800
Good evening.

111
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:21,560
Tomorrow?

112
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:27,230
Oh, come right over.
It's an honor to have you.

113
00:11:29,620 --> 00:11:31,360
You seem so excited.

114
00:11:31,380 --> 00:11:33,060
- Well.
- Who was it?

115
00:11:33,240 --> 00:11:36,470
Ajarn Thaworn.
He's got a new book out.

116
00:11:36,470 --> 00:11:38,920
And he's gonna...
drop a copy off for me.

117
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:41,510
Grandpa's teacher
is still going strong?

118
00:11:41,530 --> 00:11:43,180
- Mm-hmm.
- Such a long life.

119
00:11:43,270 --> 00:11:45,720
Heh...no, no.
He's about my age really.

120
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,760
He got into the industry earlier.

121
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:54,240
You see my trophy?
The Golden Pen Award.

122
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:57,600
I earned it the year
Ajarn Thaworn was on the committee.

123
00:11:58,240 --> 00:12:00,360
He handed it to me.

124
00:12:00,380 --> 00:12:01,840
Hmm...

125
00:12:02,340 --> 00:12:06,680
Nice. Seeing old friends ought to
put some fire back in your writing.

126
00:12:06,680 --> 00:12:07,920
Yeah. Exactly.

127
00:12:25,690 --> 00:12:29,940
"Golden Pen Award, Dec 6, 1973
Somsak Prasitphithaya"

128
00:12:40,180 --> 00:12:42,760
"Hey, so what about
this boyfriend of yours?"

129
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:44,360
"Talk to me."

130
00:12:46,210 --> 00:12:48,800
Hey, Guy. Feeling better?

131
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:51,240
Mm-hmm. Pretty good now.

132
00:12:52,030 --> 00:12:52,790
Good.

133
00:12:52,810 --> 00:12:55,140
Yeah, my grandma's got it too,
just like Save's grandpa.

134
00:12:55,390 --> 00:12:57,720
Mm-hmm, the elderly get that a lot.
It's awful.

135
00:12:58,560 --> 00:12:59,560
Got what a lot?

136
00:12:59,590 --> 00:13:01,160
Oh, you don't know?

137
00:13:02,440 --> 00:13:05,720
Save's grandpa got scam call.
They took all his money.

138
00:13:05,720 --> 00:13:07,240
What? Since when?

139
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:08,840
Two days ago.

140
00:13:37,250 --> 00:13:39,320
Hey, so what about your boyfriend?

141
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:42,440
Come on.

142
00:13:43,120 --> 00:13:45,880
Your grandfather,
you weren't going to tell me?

143
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:50,560
Well, you were sick.

144
00:13:51,610 --> 00:13:53,040
Didn't want to pile on.

145
00:13:54,040 --> 00:13:55,080
Is he okay?

146
00:13:58,200 --> 00:13:59,800
No, not really.

147
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:02,840
But he'll get through it.

148
00:14:03,780 --> 00:14:04,920
He's tough.

149
00:14:06,200 --> 00:14:07,200
Mm-hmm.

150
00:14:10,580 --> 00:14:13,240
Well, I got the cold from my mom.

151
00:14:14,130 --> 00:14:15,080
Mom.

152
00:14:15,080 --> 00:14:17,840
Yeah, my mom. I have no boyfriend.
I was messing with you.

153
00:14:18,520 --> 00:14:21,320
Oh-ho. I actually fell for that.

154
00:14:22,790 --> 00:14:24,160
You're so gullible.

155
00:14:25,960 --> 00:14:28,230
Hey, thanks for yesterday.

156
00:14:28,310 --> 00:14:30,050
Even with everything
you had going on.

157
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:34,040
It was nothing.
You've done a lot more for me.

158
00:14:35,030 --> 00:14:36,600
I can do more than yesterday.

159
00:14:42,920 --> 00:14:44,440
Hey, whatchu doing?

160
00:14:44,860 --> 00:14:47,560
Oh, you were smiling.
I want to save it.

161
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:51,200
I didn't consent to this.
You know PDPA? Delete it.

162
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:52,200
No.

163
00:14:52,220 --> 00:14:54,600
Why? I like it.
Something to look at.

164
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:00,720
Fine, now you smile.
I'll take one snap.

165
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:03,920
Give me a real smile.

166
00:15:04,190 --> 00:15:05,280
This is a real smile.

167
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:09,920
Wait, you actually took it?

168
00:15:10,320 --> 00:15:12,480
That's awful. Delete it.

169
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:15,420
- You said I could take it.
- Now, I'm telling you to delete it.

170
00:15:15,680 --> 00:15:17,520
Sorry. I'm keeping it.

171
00:15:22,490 --> 00:15:23,490
Come get it then.

172
00:15:24,600 --> 00:15:25,880
- Come get it.
- Fine.

173
00:15:28,390 --> 00:15:30,000
Good day, Ajarn.

174
00:15:30,300 --> 00:15:32,900
Good day. Khun Sak never changes.

175
00:15:32,920 --> 00:15:34,600
Always formality when we meet.

176
00:15:34,600 --> 00:15:38,080
Well, I have the utmost respect
for your knowledge.

177
00:15:38,080 --> 00:15:39,640
Please let me wai.
(respectful gesture)

178
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:42,960
- Right this way, please.
- Yes, yes.

179
00:15:47,870 --> 00:15:48,840
This is my mother.

180
00:15:48,870 --> 00:15:52,190
Oh, good day, ma'am.
She's looking well.

181
00:15:52,500 --> 00:15:54,240
Better than the rest of us,
probably.

182
00:15:54,240 --> 00:15:55,760
- Haha.
- Haha.

183
00:16:07,880 --> 00:16:09,520
Thank you so much, Ajarn.

184
00:16:09,800 --> 00:16:11,420
Among writers of our generation,

185
00:16:11,610 --> 00:16:15,300
you're the only one
still putting out new books.

186
00:16:15,300 --> 00:16:17,530
The rest have retired.

187
00:16:17,680 --> 00:16:21,200
Readers keep asking,
so I keep writing.

188
00:16:21,220 --> 00:16:22,010
Sure.

189
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:26,320
Easy enough. Whatever's in my head,
I put on the page.

190
00:16:26,320 --> 00:16:30,000
Ah, but every time you do that,

191
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:33,640
that book ends up winning an award.

192
00:16:35,520 --> 00:16:36,800
With good sales, of course.

193
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:39,880
You should come out of retirement.

194
00:16:40,520 --> 00:16:42,600
Your style will
shake things up again.

195
00:16:42,880 --> 00:16:45,680
Oh, that ship has sailed for me.

196
00:16:46,150 --> 00:16:49,080
Better to let the new generation
have their moment.

197
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:51,000
They're out of their depth.

198
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:53,760
Fiction these days
has really gone downhill.

199
00:16:53,960 --> 00:16:57,240
Oh? What have you been reading?

200
00:16:57,520 --> 00:16:59,190
Just grazing, really.

201
00:16:59,470 --> 00:17:03,530
But people tell me things,
especially, the BL fiction.

202
00:17:03,560 --> 00:17:04,600
It's everywhere now.

203
00:17:04,960 --> 00:17:06,680
Like surface scum.

204
00:17:06,960 --> 00:17:08,720
Oh, your grandson
writes in that space.

205
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:11,400
Ah...yes, sir.

206
00:17:13,170 --> 00:17:14,640
How did you know that?

207
00:17:15,060 --> 00:17:16,520
Khun Worachai mentioned it.

208
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:20,760
And have you...
read any of it?

209
00:17:21,680 --> 00:17:25,680
Feel free to criticize.
I'll pass it along to him.

210
00:17:26,220 --> 00:17:28,840
It starts with two men
having feelings for each other.

211
00:17:29,340 --> 00:17:32,080
I understand
people have different views.

212
00:17:32,300 --> 00:17:34,880
But that's not a value
I can get behind.

213
00:17:36,440 --> 00:17:39,040
I assume you feel the same way.

214
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:44,680
And if I don't?
If I stand behind him?

215
00:17:45,220 --> 00:17:47,000
I'd be surprised.

216
00:17:47,320 --> 00:17:50,000
And I'd want to hear
what you have to say.

217
00:17:50,540 --> 00:17:55,360
But as it stands, his work has been
very well received.

218
00:17:55,920 --> 00:17:58,640
And it's found
quite a wide audience.

219
00:17:59,120 --> 00:18:00,770
A wide audience?

220
00:18:01,270 --> 00:18:02,930
That doesn't necessarily mean much.

221
00:18:03,800 --> 00:18:07,400
Lowbrow, salacious things
tend to sell, don't they?

222
00:18:07,610 --> 00:18:10,720
If sales were the standard,
they'd be award-winners.

223
00:18:11,020 --> 00:18:11,490
Heh.

224
00:18:11,910 --> 00:18:15,090
Comparing a young adult novel
to a dirty book

225
00:18:15,090 --> 00:18:17,030
seems a stretch, doesn't it?

226
00:18:17,450 --> 00:18:20,920
Both, after all,
qualify as literature.

227
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:25,320
Times change.
Tastes change with them.

228
00:18:25,510 --> 00:18:31,120
So shifting along with that,
I'd say that's perfectly natural.

229
00:18:31,440 --> 00:18:34,920
Change for the better, I'd agree.
That's worth celebrating.

230
00:18:35,680 --> 00:18:37,720
But this is dragging
the whole industry down.

231
00:18:38,150 --> 00:18:40,760
I don't think
it's gone that far, sir.

232
00:18:41,160 --> 00:18:46,160
Hmph...defending him
like a loving grandpa, I see.

233
00:18:46,570 --> 00:18:50,080
If I could take back your award,
I would.

234
00:18:52,390 --> 00:18:55,240
Has time changed your views on it?

235
00:19:04,860 --> 00:19:07,120
Well. Never mind.

236
00:19:07,420 --> 00:19:09,230
Pity our views no longer align.

237
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:12,360
But nothing lasts forever, does it?

238
00:19:13,440 --> 00:19:17,280
I came today with hope
you'd pass a word to your grandson.

239
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:19,160
Something to think over.

240
00:19:19,480 --> 00:19:21,800
Whether you do it or not depends on

241
00:19:21,800 --> 00:19:24,440
what kind of world
you want to leave behind.

242
00:19:29,340 --> 00:19:31,480
Uh...lunch is ready.

243
00:19:32,980 --> 00:19:36,700
Thanks, I'm afraid I can't stay.
I have somewhere to be.

244
00:19:37,640 --> 00:19:38,960
Let me walk you out, sir.

245
00:19:54,400 --> 00:19:55,400
Dad.

246
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:58,170
Don't let what that man said
get to you.

247
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:00,160
Exactly.

248
00:20:00,960 --> 00:20:03,640
So many readers love your novel.

249
00:20:09,260 --> 00:20:11,900
Enjoy your meal. I'm not hungry.

250
00:20:26,190 --> 00:20:27,560
What a day.

251
00:20:28,720 --> 00:20:31,760
I thought an old friend's visit
would do some good.

252
00:20:32,510 --> 00:20:35,600
Well, a friend or a viper,
hard to tell.

253
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:37,010
See.

254
00:20:37,350 --> 00:20:40,720
Falling for scammers
makes him feel bad enough.

255
00:20:41,360 --> 00:20:43,620
And now he's spiraling
over what people say.

256
00:20:44,080 --> 00:20:46,160
Who was that man anyway?

257
00:20:46,480 --> 00:20:48,160
A master writer he looks up to.

258
00:20:49,360 --> 00:20:51,480
Now he'll be overthinking
what that man said.

259
00:20:54,710 --> 00:20:55,710
Huh.

260
00:21:23,520 --> 00:21:27,120
If I could take back your award,
I would.

261
00:21:27,930 --> 00:21:30,840
Has time changed your views on it?

262
00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:45,410
Whew.

263
00:21:57,430 --> 00:21:58,430
Grandpa.

264
00:21:59,540 --> 00:22:01,750
Got any writing done?
I'll type it in for you.

265
00:22:02,110 --> 00:22:03,320
Readers are waiting.

266
00:22:13,720 --> 00:22:16,640
Hey, nothing new since yesterday?

267
00:22:17,160 --> 00:22:19,120
Haven't you written a single word?

268
00:22:20,680 --> 00:22:21,960
Just a bit of a headache.

269
00:22:22,470 --> 00:22:23,470
Oh.

270
00:22:24,870 --> 00:22:27,080
What's wrong? Are you ill?

271
00:22:28,040 --> 00:22:29,040
It's nothing.

272
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:31,120
Still stressed?

273
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:35,960
Just go. I'd like time alone.

274
00:23:04,460 --> 00:23:08,070
Mom, Dad, is Grandpa okay?
He has gone quiet again.

275
00:23:08,520 --> 00:23:12,800
That Ajarn came by today
and tore into his novel.

276
00:23:13,120 --> 00:23:14,120
Tore into it how?

277
00:23:14,320 --> 00:23:17,800
He said your grandpa
had changed his views,

278
00:23:18,080 --> 00:23:20,240
encouraged you to write BL fiction,

279
00:23:20,240 --> 00:23:22,600
and threatened to take back
the award he once gave him.

280
00:23:23,680 --> 00:23:28,720
He thought you wrote it,
so he had him relay the message.

281
00:23:28,720 --> 00:23:33,720
Well, must've hurt him pretty badly.
He hasn't eaten a thing since.

282
00:23:37,930 --> 00:23:39,130
What's this Ajarn's name?

283
00:23:39,310 --> 00:23:40,310
Thaworn.

284
00:23:41,120 --> 00:23:42,240
Where can I find him?

285
00:23:47,590 --> 00:23:50,010
"Times of Our Lives"

286
00:23:53,790 --> 00:23:55,730
I've waited years
for your new book, sir.

287
00:23:56,130 --> 00:23:59,240
I'm incredibly lucky
to meet you in person today.

288
00:23:59,640 --> 00:24:00,680
Thank you so much.

289
00:24:00,930 --> 00:24:03,760
Once I've read it,
I'll post a review.

290
00:24:03,790 --> 00:24:06,040
Please do.
Email me when you're done.

291
00:24:06,070 --> 00:24:07,070
Yes, sir.

292
00:24:16,720 --> 00:24:18,320
This isn't one of mine.

293
00:24:18,920 --> 00:24:20,040
I wrote it.

294
00:24:20,400 --> 00:24:21,560
Somsak's grandson?

295
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:22,840
Yes.

296
00:24:23,360 --> 00:24:26,200
I heard you've been
critiquing my work.

297
00:24:27,120 --> 00:24:28,240
I wanted to have a word.

298
00:24:28,560 --> 00:24:31,400
I suppose you're not happy
with what I said.

299
00:24:32,120 --> 00:24:33,680
In one of your interviews,

300
00:24:34,520 --> 00:24:36,130
you said before critiquing any work,

301
00:24:36,840 --> 00:24:39,360
one should read it thoroughly first.

302
00:24:43,220 --> 00:24:44,540
But from what I can tell,

303
00:24:45,390 --> 00:24:47,150
you haven't read mine at all.

304
00:24:51,840 --> 00:24:53,060
So I printed it out for you.

305
00:24:54,260 --> 00:24:55,880
It's not finished yet, though.

306
00:24:57,050 --> 00:24:58,070
Thank you.

307
00:25:00,990 --> 00:25:02,000
The world

308
00:25:02,960 --> 00:25:04,600
is a bigger place now, Ajarn.

309
00:25:05,400 --> 00:25:07,960
Don't keep literature
frozen in your own era.

310
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:11,920
If writers of your generation
got behind newer voices,

311
00:25:12,730 --> 00:25:15,280
I think our whole scene
could go somewhere.

312
00:25:18,490 --> 00:25:21,800
And more importantly,
if you opened your mind a little,

313
00:25:29,040 --> 00:25:32,680
today's event...
might have drawn a bigger crowd.

314
00:25:41,550 --> 00:25:43,770
"Honey Cheese Pie"

315
00:25:48,440 --> 00:25:51,080
When you're done,
feedback is welcome.

316
00:25:51,840 --> 00:25:53,360
I don't expect you to like it.

317
00:25:53,810 --> 00:25:56,960
But I hope you'll come to see
what BL fiction is worth.

318
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:35,960
Ginger tea.

319
00:26:36,280 --> 00:26:37,320
Just set it there.

320
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:00,600
- Grandpa.
- Mm-hmm.

321
00:27:02,106 --> 00:27:03,826
Don't dwell on it.

322
00:27:05,560 --> 00:27:07,920
Whatever anyone says,
that's their business.

323
00:27:08,920 --> 00:27:12,360
I think that Ajarn
is jealous of you

324
00:27:12,880 --> 00:27:15,160
because your work still has readers,

325
00:27:16,150 --> 00:27:17,600
and someone to carry it forward.

326
00:27:17,910 --> 00:27:20,050
His work? Already dead.

327
00:27:22,290 --> 00:27:25,480
You know? His signing event
barely had anyone there.

328
00:27:26,160 --> 00:27:27,200
How do you know that?

329
00:27:27,500 --> 00:27:28,500
Well...

330
00:27:29,300 --> 00:27:30,440
I went.

331
00:27:32,320 --> 00:27:34,760
You didn't do anything
out of line, did you?

332
00:27:35,880 --> 00:27:36,880
Not really.

333
00:27:37,810 --> 00:27:39,810
I went to have a word with him.

334
00:27:40,520 --> 00:27:41,980
He may not take it well,

335
00:27:43,280 --> 00:27:47,400
but a taste of his own medicine
should set him straight.

336
00:27:50,410 --> 00:27:52,000
Are you sticking up for me?

337
00:27:52,460 --> 00:27:55,640
Well, you've stuck up for me plenty.

338
00:27:57,090 --> 00:27:58,210
It's my turn.

339
00:27:58,830 --> 00:28:01,660
It's perfectly fine
if he doesn't like it.

340
00:28:02,810 --> 00:28:06,280
But it's not fine to judge
someone else's work like that.

341
00:28:09,760 --> 00:28:14,040
Honestly, I don't feel too bad
about his comments.

342
00:28:14,150 --> 00:28:15,150
Oh?

343
00:28:19,370 --> 00:28:23,080
He said I had changed
my views on things.

344
00:28:23,880 --> 00:28:27,040
But...I've given it
a lot of thought.

345
00:28:27,260 --> 00:28:29,400
Back then, I simply

346
00:28:29,850 --> 00:28:33,600
wasn't open to anything new,

347
00:28:33,830 --> 00:28:36,280
clinging only to what was,

348
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:41,200
so maybe it's a good thing
that my views have changed.

349
00:28:43,400 --> 00:28:46,840
If you've worked that out,
why are you still moping?

350
00:28:57,430 --> 00:28:58,430
Hmph.

351
00:28:58,560 --> 00:29:02,040
Probably just tired. Go on.
I'm just going to bed.

352
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:04,000
But you haven't had dinner.

353
00:29:04,470 --> 00:29:06,400
Mom said you haven't eaten all day.

354
00:29:06,700 --> 00:29:09,360
I'm not eating. I'm going to bed.

355
00:29:46,120 --> 00:29:49,440
Rise and shine, everyone. Up, up.

356
00:29:49,950 --> 00:29:51,000
It's time.

357
00:29:55,070 --> 00:29:56,920
No trumpet today?

358
00:29:56,920 --> 00:30:00,680
Oh, you're right.
Pipe, check the Director's office.

359
00:30:01,440 --> 00:30:03,320
Why me?

360
00:30:03,840 --> 00:30:05,320
You going or not?

361
00:30:05,880 --> 00:30:06,880
Going now.

362
00:30:08,880 --> 00:30:10,480
Go, go.

363
00:30:26,080 --> 00:30:27,840
Hey, Grandpa.

364
00:30:31,160 --> 00:30:33,960
Auntie Oui, Grandpa fell.

365
00:30:38,920 --> 00:30:42,080
Dad, let's get you to the doctor.

366
00:30:42,480 --> 00:30:45,210
It wasn't a hard fall.
Nothing's broken.

367
00:30:45,530 --> 00:30:46,960
Nothing took a hit.

368
00:30:49,280 --> 00:30:50,280
You sure, Grandpa?

369
00:30:50,760 --> 00:30:52,880
If you leave it,
things could get worse.

370
00:30:52,910 --> 00:30:56,600
I said I'm fine. Nothing hurts.

371
00:30:58,590 --> 00:30:59,720
Then why did you fall?

372
00:31:00,360 --> 00:31:01,360
I tripped.

373
00:31:01,520 --> 00:31:03,640
- On what, Dad?
- A table leg.

374
00:31:03,670 --> 00:31:04,760
A table leg?

375
00:31:05,040 --> 00:31:06,560
Yeah. Couldn't see it clearly.

376
00:31:07,360 --> 00:31:09,280
Couldn't see a big table leg?

377
00:31:09,280 --> 00:31:11,660
- It was in the way.
- In the way?

378
00:31:11,970 --> 00:31:15,480
The table hasn't moved in years.

379
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:35,920
Here, Grandpa.
Try reading this headline.

380
00:31:36,200 --> 00:31:38,560
Why don't you read it yourself?

381
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:40,080
Just read it to me.

382
00:31:40,680 --> 00:31:43,120
Ah...stay there. Don't come over.

383
00:31:46,680 --> 00:31:49,060
Thai...baht...

384
00:31:49,150 --> 00:31:51,800
is...unsettled.

385
00:31:51,800 --> 00:31:53,320
- Unstable.
- Unstable.

386
00:31:55,150 --> 00:31:56,150
Huh.

387
00:32:00,670 --> 00:32:01,880
You can't see clearly, huh?

388
00:32:02,200 --> 00:32:05,000
I'm old.
I can't see up close very well.

389
00:32:05,190 --> 00:32:07,960
Where are your glasses?
Why aren't you wearing them?

390
00:32:08,740 --> 00:32:11,120
I saw you put them in the drawer.

391
00:32:12,520 --> 00:32:13,600
Why aren't you using them?

392
00:32:14,200 --> 00:32:16,230
- The glasses...
- What about them?

393
00:32:17,240 --> 00:32:19,760
That's enough. Don't follow me.

394
00:32:33,520 --> 00:32:34,520
- Dad.
- Hmm?

395
00:32:34,800 --> 00:32:36,320
I've been noticing for a while now.

396
00:32:37,200 --> 00:32:38,640
His eyes are having problems.

397
00:32:39,640 --> 00:32:40,640
Should we...

398
00:32:40,800 --> 00:32:43,680
take him to get new glasses
or to get checked out?

399
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:47,410
Hmm, that's why
he's not wearing glasses.

400
00:32:48,360 --> 00:32:50,360
Fine. I'll take him myself.

401
00:32:52,440 --> 00:32:53,520
- Dad. / Father.
- Grandpa.

402
00:32:55,280 --> 00:32:58,010
The patient has cataracts
in both eyes.

403
00:33:02,900 --> 00:33:04,920
What's the treatment, Doctor?

404
00:33:04,920 --> 00:33:07,920
At this stage,
surgery is the only option.

405
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:10,480
I won't do it.
I'm not having surgery.

406
00:33:10,800 --> 00:33:13,880
But if you refuse
and let them progress,

407
00:33:14,280 --> 00:33:16,960
there's a real risk of
permanent blindness.

408
00:33:17,320 --> 00:33:20,720
And complications like glaucoma
can set in on top of that.

409
00:33:21,780 --> 00:33:23,080
Then he'll have the surgery.

410
00:33:23,910 --> 00:33:25,250
When is the earliest appointment?

411
00:33:32,020 --> 00:33:35,440
That would be around
January next year.

412
00:33:35,520 --> 00:33:36,800
- Next year.
- Next year?

413
00:33:38,280 --> 00:33:40,920
- A whole year away?
- Isn't that a bit long?

414
00:33:41,280 --> 00:33:43,400
It's the earliest appointment
we have.

415
00:33:43,880 --> 00:33:47,560
Occasionally, we can move you up

416
00:33:47,560 --> 00:33:50,720
if someone cancels.

417
00:33:51,010 --> 00:33:53,520
But that doesn't happen very often.

418
00:33:53,880 --> 00:33:56,560
In that case, I'll go with
whatever you recommend.

419
00:33:56,970 --> 00:33:59,920
Alright, I'll schedule
the surgery date.

420
00:34:05,630 --> 00:34:07,920
I think next year is too long.

421
00:34:08,480 --> 00:34:11,640
Let's go to a private hospital.
I've looked into it.

422
00:34:12,160 --> 00:34:14,440
Those are expensive.

423
00:34:15,280 --> 00:34:16,760
We'll use
the universal coverage card.

424
00:34:17,120 --> 00:34:18,600
They are not so expensive.

425
00:34:19,040 --> 00:34:21,680
Put it off, and you might start
bumping into things.

426
00:34:21,890 --> 00:34:24,480
One bad fall could cost
more than the surgery.

427
00:34:24,480 --> 00:34:27,280
Okay, Father?
I'll call a doctor for you tomorrow.

428
00:34:27,280 --> 00:34:29,000
Don't bother. I'm not going.

429
00:34:29,800 --> 00:34:31,880
You won't be able to write, Dad.

430
00:34:32,400 --> 00:34:34,470
The doctor said your vision will
keep getting worse.

431
00:34:35,080 --> 00:34:36,960
Please get it done soon.

432
00:34:37,100 --> 00:34:40,320
Today, you got lucky;
the fall wasn't serious.

433
00:34:40,320 --> 00:34:43,640
But what if next time is worse?

434
00:34:45,400 --> 00:34:48,720
Exactly. What if you
tumble down the stairs?

435
00:34:49,480 --> 00:34:50,480
Save.

436
00:34:51,560 --> 00:34:52,800
Take me upstairs.

437
00:34:57,360 --> 00:34:58,360
Now.

438
00:35:06,430 --> 00:35:07,430
I can't take this.

439
00:35:08,310 --> 00:35:11,400
I insist, Dad.
This time you must listen to me.

440
00:35:12,580 --> 00:35:16,160
Mart, call the hospital tomorrow
and book it.

441
00:35:16,160 --> 00:35:18,520
Find the earliest date they have.

442
00:35:23,870 --> 00:35:24,870
Hmph.

443
00:35:50,300 --> 00:35:54,120
You gonna talk me into this surgery?

444
00:35:55,040 --> 00:35:56,440
Save it.

445
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:09,110
My body's been
wearing down for years now.

446
00:36:09,730 --> 00:36:14,080
Whatever money we have
should go toward things that matter

447
00:36:15,050 --> 00:36:16,680
like the house debt,

448
00:36:17,210 --> 00:36:20,630
and raising all these kids.

449
00:36:20,920 --> 00:36:22,880
Those things come before my eyes.

450
00:36:23,600 --> 00:36:24,840
Back to money again.

451
00:36:27,660 --> 00:36:28,660
Huh.

452
00:36:30,120 --> 00:36:31,120
Someday, Grandpa,

453
00:36:33,040 --> 00:36:34,560
I'm gonna make it big.

454
00:36:35,640 --> 00:36:38,120
I will earn enough for everyone.

455
00:36:38,800 --> 00:36:42,200
So nobody has to worry about money.

456
00:36:43,160 --> 00:36:45,560
Don't think about that now.

457
00:36:46,940 --> 00:36:50,400
Just focus on school.

458
00:36:51,550 --> 00:36:55,760
Get the scholarship
into a good school.

459
00:36:56,320 --> 00:36:59,680
Pass the exams
into a good university.

460
00:37:01,800 --> 00:37:03,600
I will feel so happy.

461
00:37:05,920 --> 00:37:07,800
As for university fees,

462
00:37:10,080 --> 00:37:11,280
don't worry about that.

463
00:37:14,120 --> 00:37:15,360
I can get a scholarship.

464
00:37:16,680 --> 00:37:18,000
And if that doesn't work out,

465
00:37:18,940 --> 00:37:22,110
I will find a way to pay.

466
00:37:23,640 --> 00:37:24,640
Hmm?

467
00:37:31,470 --> 00:37:32,470
Get some rest, Grandpa.

468
00:38:29,030 --> 00:38:31,800
Nngh. Huk. Huk.

469
00:38:49,810 --> 00:38:53,200
Huk. Huk.

470
00:39:00,870 --> 00:39:03,720
Hngh. Hngh.

471
00:39:05,480 --> 00:39:06,920
Hmm.

472
00:39:14,370 --> 00:39:15,970
When you seemed down yesterday,

473
00:39:19,720 --> 00:39:21,520
it wasn't because of Ajarn Thaworn.

474
00:39:22,960 --> 00:39:24,480
It was because of your eyes, huh?

475
00:39:28,640 --> 00:39:32,790
I'm so sorry.
I should've asked you sooner.

476
00:39:37,700 --> 00:39:39,480
It's not your fault at all.

477
00:39:41,610 --> 00:39:44,280
Let me know if anything changes
with your eyes.

478
00:39:46,840 --> 00:39:47,840
Mm-hmm.

479
00:39:48,200 --> 00:39:49,600
Everything.

480
00:39:50,880 --> 00:39:51,880
Yeah.

481
00:39:52,890 --> 00:39:55,720
- Every little thing.
- I know, I know.

482
00:39:56,960 --> 00:40:00,480
Oy...I'm not a little boy.

483
00:40:01,480 --> 00:40:03,000
Get out of here.

484
00:40:04,050 --> 00:40:05,160
I'm going to sleep.

485
00:40:18,480 --> 00:40:19,480
Huh.

486
00:40:28,160 --> 00:40:29,960
At a private hospital,

487
00:40:29,960 --> 00:40:32,760
both eyes would cost six figures.

488
00:40:34,800 --> 00:40:36,840
Should we reach out to Sun?

489
00:40:37,320 --> 00:40:38,680
Borrowing money from him again?

490
00:40:38,880 --> 00:40:42,830
What's wrong with that?
He's always been happy to help.

491
00:40:42,910 --> 00:40:46,960
- This time it's for your father.
- I told you I don't want to.

492
00:40:47,880 --> 00:40:50,280
This isn't the time
for pride, Phi Sorn.

493
00:40:51,940 --> 00:40:55,200
I'm his older brother.
I can't keep borrowing from him.

494
00:40:55,710 --> 00:40:58,200
And...he already covered
Snow's tuition.

495
00:40:58,670 --> 00:41:00,420
Now you want him
to cover Dad's surgery.

496
00:41:00,420 --> 00:41:02,480
He'll say I can't take care
of my own family.

497
00:41:03,080 --> 00:41:05,320
Nobody thinks that.

498
00:41:05,720 --> 00:41:08,640
How would you know?
I grew up with him.

499
00:41:09,360 --> 00:41:11,200
He never says it to my face,

500
00:41:11,470 --> 00:41:15,440
but his eyes have always
looked down on me like I'm nothing.

501
00:41:15,440 --> 00:41:19,640
- You're reading too much into it.
- Come on. We'll find another way.

502
00:41:42,890 --> 00:41:44,510
- Ow, who's this?
- Oh.

503
00:41:45,040 --> 00:41:46,040
Ooh.

504
00:41:46,560 --> 00:41:47,560
Save?

505
00:41:47,760 --> 00:41:51,080
Yeah, it's me.
Came to sleep beside you.

506
00:41:51,290 --> 00:41:52,520
Worried you'd fall.

507
00:41:52,600 --> 00:41:54,920
Heh...I could trip over you
in the dark.

508
00:41:55,530 --> 00:41:57,240
Find a better spot to sleep,
will you?

509
00:41:57,440 --> 00:42:00,840
Where? Next to you?

510
00:42:00,840 --> 00:42:03,920
No. Too cramped. You're enormous.

511
00:42:03,920 --> 00:42:05,360
You think you're three years old?

512
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:07,160
Then this is the spot.

513
00:42:07,960 --> 00:42:10,120
Yeah, yeah. Too tired to argue.

514
00:42:12,650 --> 00:42:13,650
Hey.

515
00:42:14,550 --> 00:42:16,940
- Where are you going?
- Bathroom.

516
00:42:17,520 --> 00:42:19,280
Okay, I will walk you there.

517
00:42:35,880 --> 00:42:36,880
Let's go.

518
00:42:45,070 --> 00:42:46,070
Hmm?

519
00:42:49,020 --> 00:42:50,060
Wait outside.

520
00:42:51,310 --> 00:42:52,310
Got it.

521
00:42:54,450 --> 00:42:55,450
All good?

522
00:43:23,640 --> 00:43:27,240
"Waiting to read new chapter."
"I check on it every day."

523
00:43:34,920 --> 00:43:37,500
"Between Us in the Deep Forest"

524
00:44:01,820 --> 00:44:02,820
Alright.

525
00:44:03,660 --> 00:44:05,160
I'm sure I've got
writer's blood in me.

526
00:44:10,210 --> 00:44:11,210
Okay.

527
00:44:19,710 --> 00:44:20,830
Read this for me.

528
00:44:21,160 --> 00:44:22,080
What's this?

529
00:44:22,080 --> 00:44:24,560
The novel. I'm continuing
from where Grandpa left off.

530
00:44:24,960 --> 00:44:26,640
Oh-ho. Think you can pull that off?

531
00:44:27,440 --> 00:44:29,200
I said read it, not roast it.

532
00:44:33,580 --> 00:44:38,400
Since then, Somporn could feel Anan
had changed completely.

533
00:44:38,720 --> 00:44:41,800
He was already attentive to him.
Now, he was even more so.

534
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:43,000
'Hungry yet?'

535
00:44:43,720 --> 00:44:44,720
Hmm?

536
00:44:45,980 --> 00:44:50,880
The way Anan talked felt
much more tender now.

537
00:44:51,920 --> 00:44:53,160
'Nibble.'

538
00:44:55,560 --> 00:44:56,800
Heh.

539
00:44:56,800 --> 00:44:58,480
Relentless, Anan kept nibbling.

540
00:44:59,040 --> 00:45:01,320
Sure he'd get Somporn to crack.

541
00:45:01,320 --> 00:45:02,400
But maybe not yet.

542
00:45:09,040 --> 00:45:10,040
Not good enough.

543
00:45:10,280 --> 00:45:11,440
Are you messing with me?

544
00:45:12,560 --> 00:45:15,400
Honestly, the readers
are going to riot.

545
00:45:15,750 --> 00:45:19,240
One line in, and I can tell
it's not Grandpa writing.

546
00:45:21,260 --> 00:45:22,800
Let me say something, Phi Save.

547
00:45:23,170 --> 00:45:23,740
Yeah.

548
00:45:23,760 --> 00:45:27,630
It's like you've ruined
everything Grandpa built.

549
00:45:28,480 --> 00:45:30,060
Burn.

550
00:45:32,350 --> 00:45:33,470
I knew it.

551
00:45:34,320 --> 00:45:36,120
How could I ever write like Grandpa?

552
00:45:43,840 --> 00:45:45,120
Don't force it, Phi Save.

553
00:45:45,760 --> 00:45:49,280
Only Grandpa can write
what's between Somporn and Anan.

554
00:45:54,840 --> 00:45:55,840
Huh.

555
00:46:04,850 --> 00:46:06,320
"Hi, I work in modeling."

556
00:46:06,320 --> 00:46:08,760
"Looking for fresh faces
for a BL series."

557
00:46:08,760 --> 00:46:10,560
"Interested in having a chat?"

558
00:46:11,120 --> 00:46:12,240
Is this a scam?

559
00:46:23,920 --> 00:46:25,120
I want to make some money.

560
00:46:26,440 --> 00:46:27,960
Where do you work part-time?

561
00:46:27,960 --> 00:46:30,720
I talked to him. He wouldn't budge.

562
00:46:30,720 --> 00:46:34,440
He's waiting for
the public hospital.

563
00:46:34,970 --> 00:46:36,640
Why is he so stubborn?

564
00:46:37,400 --> 00:46:39,840
He wants to save the money
for something else.

565
00:46:40,240 --> 00:46:42,200
Now the bank's calling again.

566
00:46:42,480 --> 00:46:45,840
We missed last month's payment.

567
00:46:46,620 --> 00:46:49,800
Life's been rough lately.
One thing after another.

568
00:47:50,590 --> 00:47:51,640
Hey, Sun.

569
00:47:55,160 --> 00:47:57,080
What are you snapping away at?

570
00:47:57,550 --> 00:48:00,360
Practicing, Dad.
I just shoot whatever I see.

571
00:48:01,520 --> 00:48:02,790
You're burning through film.

572
00:48:06,220 --> 00:48:07,220
Hmm.

573
00:48:22,020 --> 00:48:23,020
Give me that.

574
00:48:44,360 --> 00:48:46,040
17 out of 50?

575
00:48:52,120 --> 00:48:54,680
Dad, why are you
going through my stuff?

576
00:48:55,720 --> 00:48:57,600
You failed an exam
and didn't tell me?

577
00:48:57,960 --> 00:49:00,920
Everyone was worried about Grandpa.
I couldn't bring this up.

578
00:49:01,080 --> 00:49:03,160
So you were hiding it.

579
00:49:04,520 --> 00:49:05,600
There it is.

580
00:49:05,600 --> 00:49:07,160
What are you two arguing about?

581
00:49:08,590 --> 00:49:10,400
Any other subjects
you're failing too?

582
00:49:10,750 --> 00:49:12,920
Just math. I don't like it.

583
00:49:12,920 --> 00:49:14,520
You still have to learn it.

584
00:49:14,520 --> 00:49:17,000
I'm not asking you
to get perfect scores.

585
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:18,360
How many times have you failed?

586
00:49:19,880 --> 00:49:23,160
Hmm...easy, Dad. I'll tutor her.

587
00:49:23,630 --> 00:49:25,760
Her other grades
aren't so good either.

588
00:49:26,080 --> 00:49:30,500
All you do is read novels,
check social media and dance around.

589
00:49:31,700 --> 00:49:32,920
Give me your phone.

590
00:49:37,120 --> 00:49:38,800
Snow, give me your phone.

591
00:49:40,720 --> 00:49:43,560
- Snow, don't give me attitude.
- Dad, please don't.

592
00:49:44,800 --> 00:49:48,760
From now on, no Internet, no novels,
until you pass.

593
00:49:49,200 --> 00:49:51,680
- That has nothing to do with it.
- Of course, it does.

594
00:49:51,890 --> 00:49:53,880
Use that time to study.

595
00:49:54,320 --> 00:49:57,320
Your uncle went out of his way
to pay your tuition.

596
00:49:58,120 --> 00:50:01,920
Stop it, Dad. Have I ever asked
for an expensive school?

597
00:50:02,760 --> 00:50:05,280
No, I just wanted
to be with my friends.

598
00:50:06,140 --> 00:50:08,260
You never listen to me.

599
00:50:08,600 --> 00:50:11,440
Fine, it doesn't matter
which school.

600
00:50:11,620 --> 00:50:14,080
You can't go very far
with grades like that.

601
00:50:15,160 --> 00:50:19,160
Just like you, Dad.
You didn't do well in school either.

602
00:50:19,160 --> 00:50:20,160
Snow.

603
00:50:26,350 --> 00:50:27,480
Huh.

604
00:50:36,060 --> 00:50:37,060
Hmph.

605
00:50:39,110 --> 00:50:40,230
Oh, Snow.

606
00:50:48,530 --> 00:50:49,680
Uncle Sun.

607
00:50:51,720 --> 00:50:53,720
Dad, can I have a word?

608
00:51:00,240 --> 00:51:02,320
Your surgery, don't worry
about the cost.

609
00:51:03,380 --> 00:51:04,380
I'll cover it.

610
00:51:05,360 --> 00:51:07,600
Today, you can go to
the private hospital.

611
00:51:08,200 --> 00:51:09,200
No.

612
00:51:10,290 --> 00:51:12,680
I already scheduled a doctor.

613
00:51:13,320 --> 00:51:14,960
But it's still a year out, Dad.

614
00:51:15,920 --> 00:51:18,000
I talked to a friend who's a doctor.

615
00:51:18,060 --> 00:51:19,370
He says if you wait,

616
00:51:20,440 --> 00:51:21,620
it'll only get worse.

617
00:51:22,880 --> 00:51:25,480
Then let it. I can wait.

618
00:51:25,960 --> 00:51:27,160
You can't, Dad.

619
00:51:27,800 --> 00:51:30,280
Your vision's already going,
isn't it?

620
00:51:30,640 --> 00:51:32,120
You can't walk without Save's help.

621
00:51:33,200 --> 00:51:35,440
I don't see him
complaining about it.

622
00:51:35,960 --> 00:51:36,960
Huh.

623
00:51:36,970 --> 00:51:38,970
If you won't let me help
with the surgery,

624
00:51:39,690 --> 00:51:41,400
then at least let me help
with the house.

625
00:51:43,240 --> 00:51:44,440
What help?

626
00:51:44,880 --> 00:51:47,080
You should sell Saeng Karun
to my company.

627
00:51:48,280 --> 00:51:50,760
What does your company
have to do with this?

628
00:51:51,080 --> 00:51:54,520
My boss is willing to buy it
above market value.

629
00:51:55,040 --> 00:51:57,600
Better than losing it to the bank
and getting nothing.

630
00:51:57,880 --> 00:52:00,920
You went and arranged all this
without a word to me?

631
00:52:02,480 --> 00:52:05,160
I know how much
this house means to you, Dad.

632
00:52:05,480 --> 00:52:09,160
But maybe it's time to let go.

633
00:52:10,040 --> 00:52:13,680
- You don't understand.
- Why wouldn't I?

634
00:52:14,440 --> 00:52:17,760
I grew up here.
I'm attached to this place too.

635
00:52:18,040 --> 00:52:19,200
Not really.

636
00:52:20,400 --> 00:52:24,000
You left at eighteen or nineteen.

637
00:52:24,600 --> 00:52:27,840
After you were done with school,
why didn't you come back?

638
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:32,400
I'm telling you for the last time.

639
00:52:32,760 --> 00:52:35,880
I'm not...selling this house.

640
00:52:36,880 --> 00:52:40,120
And I won't accept anything
from you.

641
00:52:40,680 --> 00:52:41,680
Why, Dad?

642
00:52:43,610 --> 00:52:46,920
Why won't you let me
help with anything?

643
00:52:48,350 --> 00:52:49,560
You can go now.

644
00:52:50,520 --> 00:52:51,520
Go.

645
00:52:53,360 --> 00:52:55,160
Is it because
I'm not what you wanted?

646
00:52:57,890 --> 00:53:00,200
Do you actually hate me, Dad?

647
00:53:03,440 --> 00:53:06,520
When I was a boy, you never once
looked me in the eye.

648
00:53:07,050 --> 00:53:08,160
Why, Dad?

649
00:53:09,160 --> 00:53:11,080
Am I really that much
of a disappointment?

650
00:53:17,520 --> 00:53:18,840
I never said that.

651
00:53:18,840 --> 00:53:21,680
Then why?
Why do you always push me away?

652
00:53:22,900 --> 00:53:23,900
You know, Dad?

653
00:53:24,090 --> 00:53:26,880
I never wanted to stay here
because of you.

654
00:53:28,040 --> 00:53:30,320
Sun, that's enough.

655
00:53:30,350 --> 00:53:32,760
You cannot
speak to your father like that.

656
00:53:33,420 --> 00:53:35,870
You know how hurt he's been

657
00:53:35,890 --> 00:53:38,320
that you didn't grow up
the way he expected?

658
00:53:46,030 --> 00:53:47,400
You made him that angry;

659
00:53:47,400 --> 00:53:49,440
don't you feel any remorse
and try to make it right?

660
00:53:49,440 --> 00:53:51,320
Thanks for wanting to help.

661
00:53:51,320 --> 00:53:53,760
But some things...can't be fixed.

662
00:53:54,920 --> 00:53:56,320
Now that we've made up.

663
00:53:56,680 --> 00:53:57,840
What are we now?

664
00:53:57,870 --> 00:54:01,080
The story of Somporn and Anan
isn't over.

665
00:54:01,230 --> 00:54:06,000
A writer can't abandon
their characters or their readers.

666
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:11,720
The world keeps
turning every day.

667
00:54:11,720 --> 00:54:17,240
And we keep
turning in its play.

668
00:54:17,240 --> 00:54:20,400
Just open up, we'll learn it in.

669
00:54:20,400 --> 00:54:23,080
We just might see
the world within.

670
00:54:23,080 --> 00:54:26,960
Let's walk together,
day by day.

671
00:54:26,960 --> 00:54:32,360
Come take the step,
what do you say?

672
00:54:38,730 --> 00:54:42,290
Let us be real,
not dreaming away,

673
00:54:42,290 --> 00:54:46,240
We'll walk in the light
of a new day.

674
00:54:46,240 --> 00:54:51,320
No one can tell
what tomorrow may say.

675
00:54:51,320 --> 00:54:53,760
Wherever the gentle wind blows,

676
00:54:53,760 --> 00:54:56,520
let our hearts flow,
soft and slow.

677
00:54:56,520 --> 00:55:01,440
And land where
our hearts both grow.

678
00:55:01,700 --> 00:55:07,680
The world keeps
turning every day.

679
00:55:07,680 --> 00:55:13,000
And we keep
turning in its play.

680
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:16,360
Just open up, we'll learn it in.

681
00:55:16,360 --> 00:55:18,920
We just might see
the world within.

682
00:55:18,920 --> 00:55:23,000
Let's walk together,
day by day.

683
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:28,040
Come take the step,
what do you say?
